# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aberdeen-maternity-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The initiative is a global effort for improving the role of maternity services to enable mothers to breastfeed babies for the best start in life.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It aims at improving the care of pregnant women, mothers and newborns at health facilities that provide maternity services for protecting, promoting and supporting breastfeeding, in accordance with the International Code of Marketing of Breast-milk Substitutes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] UNICEF, WHO, and many national government health agencies recommend that babies are breastfed exclusively for their first six months of life.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Studies have shown that breastfed babies are less likely to suffer from serious illnesses, including gastroenteritis, asthma, eczema, and respiratory and ear infections.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Adults who were breastfed as babies may be less likely to develop risk factors for heart disease such as obesity and high blood pressure.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] There are benefits for mothers too: women who don't breastfeed have increased risk of developing heart disease, hypertension, diabetes, high cholesterol, breast cancer, ovarian cancer and hip fractures in later life.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The BFHI aims to increase the numbers of babies who are exclusively breastfed worldwide, a goal which the WHO estimates could contribute to avoiding over a million child deaths each year, and potentially many premature maternal deaths as well.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Comply fully with the International Code of Marketing of Breast-milk Substitutes and relevant World Health Assembly resolutions.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Have a written infant feeding policy that is routinely communicated to staff and parents.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Establish ongoing monitoring and data-management systems.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Ensure that staff have sufficient knowledge, competence and skills to support breastfeeding.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Discuss the importance and management of breastfeeding with pregnant women and their families.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Facilitate immediate and uninterrupted skin-to-skin contact and support mothers to initiate breastfeeding as soon as possible after birth.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Support mothers to initiate and maintain breastfeeding and manage common difficulties.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Do not provide breastfed newborns any food or fluids other than breast milk, unless medically indicated.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Enable mothers and their infants to remain together and to practise rooming-in 24 hours a day.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Support mothers to recognize and respond to their infants' cues for feeding.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Counsel mothers on the use and risks of feeding bottles, teats and pacifiers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Coordinate discharge so that parents and their infants have timely access to ongoing support and care.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The program also restricts use by the hospital of free formula or other infant care aids provided by formula companies and recommends that when formula is medically needed, it should be given in a small cup or spoon, rather than a bottle and should only be used to supplement breastfeeding.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2011, approximately 15,000 facilities in more than 152 countries had been inspected and accredited as "Baby-Friendly." The number of accredited hospitals has continued to grow.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2019, a survey found that 28% of the hospitals in the US were registered as Baby Friendly.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The World Health Organization recommends that if a mother is unable to breastfeed, chooses not to breastfeed, or if her baby (often premature) shows signs that it isn't getting enough breast-milk, a healthy wet nurse or milk from a donor is a healthy alternative to formula.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A special formula is manufactured for premature babies, although the World Health Organization recommends it only if breast-milk is medically not an option such as if a premature baby has to be fed formula through a tube to maintain a healthy weight.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The World Health Organization advocates the importance of a baby being close to its mother whenever possible even if the mother does not breastfeed.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In Canada, the provinces of Quebec and New Brunswick have mandated the implementation of the BFHI.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] All public health units in Ontario have been required to work towards having BFI designation since 2011.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2012, the Ministry of Health and Long Term Care in Ontario added BFI status to their progress indicators for Public Health Units thus requiring all Public Health Units in Ontario to begin implementation of BFI.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Other provinces and territories are implementing strategies at regional and local levels.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2008, 18 health care facilities (9 hospitals & birthing centres and 9 community health services) had been designated "Baby-Friendly" across the country.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Women's Hospital and Health Centre has been recognized as a breast-feeding and "baby-friendly" hospital by the World Health Organization (WHO) and UNICEF since 2008.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It is the largest hospital in Canada to receive the designation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] China, now has more than 6,000 Baby-Friendly Hospitals, exclusive breastfeeding in rural areas rose from 29 per cent in 1992 to 68 per cent in 1994; in urban areas, the increase was from 10 per cent to 48 per cent.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In Cuba, 49 of the country's 56 hospitals and maternity facilities have been designated as "baby-friendly".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In the six years following the initiation of the BFHI program, the rate of exclusive breastfeeding at four months almost tripled - from 25 per cent in 1990 to 72 per cent in 1996.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In Hong Kong several hospitals have shown interest in being designated Baby Friendly.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] However, only Queen Elizabeth Hospital has advanced past the Award of Level 2 Participation stage and is well on its way to receiving BFHI accreditation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The BFHI started in Ireland in 1998 under the auspices of the Irish Health Promoting Hospitals Network (a WHO programme).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The BFHI in Ireland became an independent registered charity in mid-2016 and changed their name to Baby Friendly Health Initiative.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Sweden is considered the global leader in terms of BFHI implementation: four years after the programme was introduced in 1993, all of the then 65 maternity centres in the country had been designated "baby-friendly".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2014 78.60% of babies were born in BFHI hospitals.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Between 2001 and 2013, the increase in certified hospitals was from 38 to 176.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The UNICEF UK Baby Friendly Initiative was launched in the United Kingdom in 1995.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The Initiative works with the National Health Service (NHS) to ensure a high standard of care for pregnant women and breastfeeding mothers and babies in hospitals and community health settings.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The Baby Friendly Initiative accredits health-care facilities that adopt internationally recognised best practice standards for breastfeeding.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] During each stage of accreditation, the Initiative provides support as facilities implement standards relating to policies and procedures, staff education, effective auditing, educating pregnant women and mothers, and other relevant areas.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 1998, its principles were extended to cover the work of community health-care services with the *Seven Point Plan for the Promotion, Protection and Support of Breastfeeding in Community Health Care Settings*.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It has been estimated that if all babies were breastfed, over £35m would be saved by the NHS in England and Wales each year in treating gastroenteritis alone.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Despite that, in 2013 breastfeeding rates in the UK were amongst the lowest in Europe: 78 per cent of babies born in the UK were breastfed at birth, falling to 63 per cent at one week.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Only one in five babies still received breastmilk at six months.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2013 the success of the initiative in Scotland showed that 90% of Scottish mothers gave birth in a UNICEF-accredited Baby Friendly hospital.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] This compared to 30% of mothers in England, 58% for Wales and 57% in Northern Ireland.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The first hospitals verified as Baby-Friendly in the US were on the Pacific Coast.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The first US hospital to receive this designation was Evergreen Hospital Medical Center, in Kirkland, Washington, which was certified in September 1996.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] All of these early adopters were able to achieve 100% breastfeeding initiation rates.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In New York City, the Harlem Hospital Center was the first hospital to receive the "Baby Friendly" certification granted by Baby-Friendly USA for the city in 2008.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2011, New York University Langone Medical Center became the second hospital to receive the Baby-Friendly Hospital designation in New York City.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The Johns Hopkins Hospital in Maryland describes the process of receiving the Baby Friendly designation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2 May 2018, the United States had 512 hospitals that hold the Baby-Friendly designation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] This translates to 24.57% of annual births.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2019, 28% of hospitals in the U.S. have been accredited by the WHO.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] One group of authors expressed concerns in a paper published in October 2016.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It questioned whether full compliance with the ten steps of the initiative might inadvertently lead to the promotion of potentially hazardous practices and/or counterproductive outcomes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Specific concerns described in this paper included increased risk of sudden unexpected postnatal collapse, rigidly-enforced rooming-in practices leading to exhausted or heavily medicated mothers caring for newborns, and an unnecessary ban on pacifier use.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A 2016 systematic review examined the impact of BFHI implementation on breastfeeding and child health outcomes worldwide and in the United States.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors suggested that following the BFHI Ten Steps had a positive impact on short, medium, and long-term breastfeeding outcomes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] However, they warned their results for the United States explaining "All of the United States BFHI evidence comes from observational studies, the vast majority of which are of very low or low quality.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Although there is consistent empirical evidence that BFHI has led to improvements in breastfeeding outcomes in the very short and short terms, its impact on BF outcomes in the long term remains unclear".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Looking at 58 studies, the review found that community support was the key to long-term sustainability of breastfeeding that was initiated in the BFHI hospital setting.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A study published in the *Journal of Pediatrics* in 2019 showed that increased rates of implementation of the BFHI were temporally associated with a decrease in the rate of infant deaths in the first six days after birth.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors said that their findings dispelled the suggestion that hospital-based breastfeeding initiatives might increase infant death from asphyxiation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors did not discuss the other potential harms to mother and baby that critics have raised, such as increased incidence of neonate hospital admission due to dehydration and poor maternal mental health outcomes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A 2017 study focusing on hospital readmission among infants based on method of feeding raised concerns that exclusive breastfeeding is linked to double the rate of readmission to hospital among neonates as compared to formula feeding.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Critics of the Baby Friendly Initiative point to this type of data and several anecdotal stories of babies harmed at hospitals following the Baby Friendly Initiative as evidence that the current guidelines are potentially harmful and not meeting the needs of mother or baby.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A 2021 review of systematic reviews raised further doubts about some of the claims raised in support of the Baby Friendly Initiative, as it was found that the majority of cited studies concluding benefits of implementation were of low or very low quality.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors raised a number of concerns surrounding quantification of long-term outcomes on maternal and child health apart from breastfeeding initiation, and suggested that outcomes may differ substantially among poor and wealthy countries.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Additionally, the authors described potential negative outcomes associated with full implementation of the Baby Friendly Initiative, including promoting unrealistic breastfeeding expectations, mothers feeling pressured to breastfeed, and increased feelings of maternal guilt.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Further high quality studies were recommended to evaluate both long-term breastfeeding outcomes and other aspects of maternal health.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] About 33% of deaths from cancer are caused by tobacco and alcohol, obesity, lack of fruit and vegetables in the diet and lack of exercise.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Other factors include certain infections, exposure to ionizing radiation, and environmental pollutants.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Infection with specific viruses, bacteria, and parasites causes approximately 16–18% of cancers worldwide.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] These infectious agents include *Helicobacter pylori*, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, and HPV.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) does not directly cause cancer, but it causes immune deficiency that can increase the risk of cancer from other infections, sometimes up to several thousandfold.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Vaccination against the hepatitis B virus and the human papillomavirus have been shown to nearly eliminate the risk of cancers caused by these viruses.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] These environmental factors act, at least partly, by changing the genes of a cell.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Typically, many genetic changes are required before cancer develops.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Approximately 5–10% of cancers are due to inherited genetic defects.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer can be detected by certain signs and symptoms or screening tests.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] It is then typically further investigated by medical imaging and confirmed by biopsy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Early detection through screening is useful for cervical and colorectal cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The benefits of screening for breast cancer are controversial.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer is often treated with some combination of radiation therapy, surgery, chemotherapy and targeted therapy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] More personalized therapies that harness a patient's immune system are emerging in the field of cancer immunotherapy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Palliative care is a medical specialty that delivers advanced pain and symptom management, which may be particularly important in those with advanced disease.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The chance of survival depends on the type of cancer and extent of disease at the start of treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In children under 15 at diagnosis, the five-year survival rate in the developed world is on average 80%.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For cancer in the United States, the average five-year survival rate is 66% for all ages.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In 2015, about 90.5 million people worldwide had cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In 2019, annual cancer cases grew by 23.6 million people, and there were 10 million deaths worldwide, representing over the previous decade increases of 26% and 21%, respectively.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The most common types of cancer in males are lung cancer, prostate cancer, colorectal cancer, and stomach cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In females, the most common types are breast cancer, colorectal cancer, lung cancer, and cervical cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] If skin cancer other than melanoma were included in total new cancer cases each year, it would account for around 40% of cases.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In children, acute lymphoblastic leukemia and brain tumors are most common, except in Africa, where non-Hodgkin lymphoma occurs more often.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In 2012, about 165,000 children under 15 years of age were diagnosed with cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The risk of cancer increases significantly with age, and many cancers occur more commonly in developed countries.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Rates are increasing as more people live to an old age and as lifestyle changes occur in the developing world.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The global total economic costs of cancer were estimated at US$1.16 trillion (equivalent to $1.71 trillion in 2025) per year as of 2010.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The word comes from the ancient Greek καρκίνος, meaning 'crab' and 'tumor'.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Greek physicians Hippocrates and Galen, among others, noted the similarity of crabs to some tumors with swollen veins.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The word was introduced in English in the modern medical sense around 1600.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancers comprise a large family of diseases that involve abnormal cell growth with the potential to invade or spread to other parts of the body.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] A neoplasm or tumor is a group of cells that have undergone unregulated growth and will often form a mass or lump, but may be distributed diffusely.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] All tumor cells show the six hallmarks of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] These characteristics are required to produce a malignant tumor.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The progression from normal cells to cells that can form a detectable mass to cancer involves multiple steps known as malignant progression.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] When cancer begins, it produces no symptoms.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Signs and symptoms appear as the mass grows or ulcerates.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The findings that result depend on cancer's type and location.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Many frequently occur in individuals who have other conditions.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer can be difficult to diagnose and can be considered a "great imitator".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] People may become anxious or depressed post-diagnosis.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The risk of suicide in people with cancer is approximately double.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Local symptoms may occur due to the mass of the tumor or its ulceration.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For example, mass effects from lung cancer can block the bronchus resulting in cough or pneumonia; esophageal cancer can cause narrowing of the esophagus, making it difficult or painful to swallow; and colorectal cancer may lead to narrowing or blockages in the bowel, affecting bowel habits.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Masses in breasts or testicles may produce observable lumps.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Ulceration can cause bleeding that can lead to symptoms such as coughing up blood (lung cancer), anemia or rectal bleeding (colon cancer), blood in the urine (bladder cancer), or abnormal vaginal bleeding (endometrial or cervical cancer).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Although localized pain may occur in advanced cancer, the initial tumor is usually painless.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Some cancers can cause a buildup of fluid within the chest or abdomen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Systemic symptoms may occur due to the body's response to the cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] This may include fatigue, unintentional weight loss, or skin changes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Some cancers can cause a systemic inflammatory state that leads to ongoing muscle loss and weakness, known as cachexia.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Some cancers, such as Hodgkin's disease, leukemias, and liver or kidney cancers, can cause a persistent fever.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Shortness of breath, called dyspnea, is a common symptom of cancer and its treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The causes of cancer-related dyspnea can include tumors in or around the lung, blocked airways, fluid in the lungs, pneumonia, or treatment reactions including an allergic response.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Treatment for dyspnea in patients with advanced cancer can include fans, bilevel ventilation, acupressure/reflexology and multicomponent nonpharmacological interventions.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Some systemic symptoms of cancer are caused by hormones or other molecules produced by the tumor, known as paraneoplastic syndromes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Common paraneoplastic syndromes include hypercalcemia, which can cause altered mental state, constipation and dehydration, or hyponatremia, which can also cause altered mental status, vomiting, headaches, or seizures.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Metastasis is the spread of cancer to other locations in the body.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The dispersed tumors are called metastatic tumors, while the original is called the primary tumor.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Most cancer deaths are due to cancer that has metastasized.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Metastasis is common in the late stages of cancer and it can occur via the blood or the lymphatic system or both.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Different types of cancers tend to metastasize to particular organs.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Overall, the most common places for metastases to occur are the lungs, liver, brain, and the bones.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] While some cancers can be cured if detected early, metastatic cancer is more difficult to treat and control.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Nevertheless, some recent treatments are demonstrating encouraging results.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The majority of cancers, some 90–95% of cases, are due to environmental and lifestyle factors.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The remaining 5–10% are due to inherited genetics.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] *Environmental* refers to any cause that is not inherited, such as lifestyle, economic, and behavioral factors and not merely pollution.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Common environmental factors that contribute to cancer death include tobacco use (25–30%), diet and obesity (30–35%), infections (15–20%), radiation (both ionizing and non-ionizing, up to 10%), lack of physical activity, and pollution.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Psychological stress does not appear to be a risk factor for the onset of cancer, though it may worsen outcomes in those who already have cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Environmental or lifestyle factors that caused cancer to develop in an individual can be identified by analyzing mutational signatures from genomic sequencing of tumor DNA.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For example, this can reveal if lung cancer was caused by tobacco smoke, if skin cancer was caused by UV radiation, or if secondary cancers were caused by previous chemotherapy treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer is generally not a transmissible disease.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Exceptions include rare transmissions that occur with pregnancies and occasional organ donors.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] However, transmissible infectious diseases such as hepatitis B, Epstein–Barr, HPV and HIV infections, can contribute to the development of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Exposure to particular substances has been linked to specific types of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] These substances are called *carcinogens*.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Tobacco smoke, for example, causes 90% of lung cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Tobacco use can cause cancer throughout the body including in the mouth and throat, larynx, esophagus, stomach, bladder, kidney, cervix, colon/rectum, liver and pancreas.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Tobacco smoke contains over fifty known carcinogens, including nitrosamines and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Tobacco is responsible for about one in five cancer deaths worldwide and about one in three in the developed world.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Lung cancer death rates in the United States have mirrored smoking patterns, with increases in smoking followed by dramatic increases in lung cancer death rates and, more recently, decreases in smoking rates since the 1950s followed by decreases in lung cancer death rates in men since 1990.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Alcohol increases the risk of cancer of the breast (in women), throat, liver, osophagus, mouth, larynx, and colon.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In Western Europe, 10% of cancers in males and 3% of cancers in females are attributed to alcohol, especially liver and digestive tract cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer from work-related substance exposures may cause between 2 and 20% of cases, causing at least 200,000 deaths.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancers such as lung cancer and mesothelioma can come from inhaling tobacco smoke or asbestos fibers, or leukemia from exposure to benzene.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Exposure to perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA), which is predominantly used in the production of Teflon, has been associated with an increased risk of kidney cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Chemotherapy drugs such as platinum-based compounds are carcinogens that increase the risk of secondary cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Azathioprine, an immunosuppressive medication, is a carcinogen that can cause primary tumors to develop.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Diet, physical inactivity, and obesity are related to up to 30–35% of cancer deaths.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In the United States, excess body weight is associated with the development of many types of cancer and is a factor in 14–20% of cancer deaths.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] A UK study including data on over 5 million people showed higher body mass index to be related to at least 10 types of cancer and responsible for around 12,000 cases each year in that country.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Physical inactivity is believed to contribute to cancer risk, not only through its effect on body weight but also through negative effects on the immune system and endocrine system.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] More than half of the effect from the diet is due to overnutrition (eating too much), rather than from eating too few vegetables or other healthful foods.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Some specific foods are linked to specific cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] A high-salt diet is linked to gastric cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Aflatoxin B1, a frequent food contaminant, causes liver cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Betel nut chewing can cause oral cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] National differences in dietary practices may partly explain differences in cancer incidence.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For example, gastric cancer is more common in Japan due to its high-salt diet while colon cancer is more common in the United States.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Immigrant cancer profiles mirror those of their new country, often within one generation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Worldwide, approximately 18% of cancer deaths are related to infectious diseases.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] This proportion ranges from a high of 25% in Africa to less than 10% in the developed world.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Viruses are the usual infectious agents that cause cancer but bacteria and parasites may also play a role.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Radiation exposure such as ultraviolet radiation and radioactive material is a risk factor for cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Many non-melanoma skin cancers are due to ultraviolet radiation, mostly from sunlight.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Sources of ionizing radiation include medical imaging and radon gas.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Residential exposure to radon gas has similar cancer risks as passive smoking.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Radiation is a more potent source of cancer when combined with other cancer-causing agents, such as radon plus tobacco smoke.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Radiation can cause cancer in most parts of the body, and at any age.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Children are twice as likely to develop radiation-induced leukemia as adults; radiation exposure before birth has ten times the effect.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Medical use of ionizing radiation is a small but growing source of radiation-induced cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Ionizing radiation may be used to treat other cancers, but this may, in some cases, induce a second form of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] It is also used in some kinds of medical imaging.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Prolonged exposure to ultraviolet radiation from the sun can lead to melanoma and other skin malignancies.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Ultraviolet radiation, especially the non-ionizing medium wave UVB, is the cause of most non-melanoma skin cancers, which are the most common forms of cancer in the world.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Non-ionizing radio frequency radiation from mobile phones, electric power transmission and other similar sources has been described as a possible carcinogen by the World Health Organization's International Agency for Research on Cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Evidence, however, has not supported a concern.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] There is no demonstrable link between mobile phone radiation and cancer risk.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Most cancers are non-hereditary (sporadic).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Hereditary cancers are caused by inherited genetics.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Less than 0.3% of the population are carriers of a genetic mutation that has a large effect on cancer risk and these cause less than 3–10% of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The relative risk of developing colorectal cancer (the cancer with the highest mortality) when a first-degree relative (parent, sibling or child) has been diagnosed with it is about 2.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The corresponding relative risk is 1.5 for lung cancer, and 1.9 for prostate cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For breast cancer, the relative risk is 1.8 with a first-degree relative having developed it at 50 years of age or older, and 3.3 when the relative developed it when being younger than 50 years of age.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Taller people have an increased risk of cancer because they have more cells than shorter people.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Since height is genetically determined to a large extent, taller people have a heritable increase in cancer risk.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Some substances cause cancer primarily through their physical, rather than chemical, effects.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] A prominent example of this is prolonged exposure to asbestos, naturally occurring mineral fibers that are a major cause of mesothelioma (cancer of the serous membrane) usually the serous membrane surrounding the lungs.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Other substances in this category, including both naturally occurring and synthetic asbestos-like fibers, such as wollastonite, attapulgite, glass wool and rock wool, are believed to have similar effects.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Non-fibrous particulate materials that cause cancer include powdered metallic cobalt and nickel and crystalline silica (quartz, cristobalite and tridymite).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Usually, physical carcinogens must get inside the body (such as through inhalation) and require years of exposure to produce cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Physical trauma resulting in cancer is relatively rare.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Claims that breaking bones resulted in bone cancer, for example, have not been proven.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Similarly, physical trauma is not accepted as a cause for cervical cancer, breast cancer or brain cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] One accepted source is frequent, long-term application of hot objects to the body.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] It is possible that repeated burns on the same part of the body, such as those produced by kanger and kairo heaters (charcoal hand warmers), may produce skin cancer, especially if carcinogenic chemicals are also present.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Frequent consumption of scalding hot tea may produce esophageal cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Generally, it is believed that cancer arises, or a pre-existing cancer is encouraged, during the process of healing, rather than directly by the trauma.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] However, repeated injuries to the same tissues might promote excessive cell proliferation, which could then increase the odds of a cancerous mutation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Chronic inflammation has been hypothesized to directly cause mutation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Inflammation can contribute to proliferation, survival, angiogenesis and migration of cancer cells by influencing the tumor microenvironment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Oncogenes build up an inflammatory pro-tumorigenic microenvironment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Hormones also play a role in the development of cancer by promoting cell proliferation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Insulin-like growth factors and their binding proteins play a key role in cancer cell proliferation, differentiation and apoptosis, suggesting possible involvement in carcinogenesis.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Hormones are important agents in sex-related cancers, such as cancer of the breast, endometrium, prostate, ovary and testis and also of thyroid cancer and bone cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For example, the daughters of women who have breast cancer have significantly higher levels of estrogen and progesterone than the daughters of women without breast cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] These higher hormone levels may explain their higher risk of breast cancer, even in the absence of a breast-cancer gene.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Similarly, men of African ancestry have significantly higher levels of testosterone than men of European ancestry and have a correspondingly higher level of prostate cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Men of Asian ancestry, with the lowest levels of testosterone-activating androstanediol glucuronide, have the lowest levels of prostate cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Other factors are relevant: obese people have higher levels of some hormones associated with cancer and a higher rate of those cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Women who take hormone replacement therapy have a higher risk of developing cancers associated with those hormones.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] On the other hand, people who exercise far more than average have lower levels of these hormones and lower risk of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Osteosarcoma may be promoted by growth hormones.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Some treatments and prevention approaches leverage this cause by artificially reducing hormone levels and thus discouraging hormone-sensitive cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] There is an association between celiac disease and an increased risk of all cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] People with untreated celiac disease have a higher risk, but this risk decreases with time after diagnosis and strict treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] This may be due to the adoption of a gluten-free diet, which seems to have a protective role against the development of malignancy in people with celiac disease.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] However, the delay in diagnosis and initiation of a gluten-free diet seems to increase the risk of malignancies.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Rates of gastrointestinal cancers are increased in people with Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis, due to chronic inflammation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Immunomodulators and biologic agents used to treat these diseases may promote the development of extra-intestinal malignancies.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer is fundamentally a disease of tissue growth regulation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For a normal cell to transform into a cancer cell, the genes that regulate cell growth and differentiation must be altered.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The affected genes are divided into two broad categories.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Oncogenes are genes that promote cell growth and reproduction.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Tumor suppressor genes are genes that inhibit cell division and survival.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Malignant transformation can occur through the formation of novel oncogenes, the inappropriate over-expression of normal oncogenes, or by the under-expression or disabling of tumor suppressor genes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Typically, changes in multiple genes are required to transform a normal cell into a cancer cell.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Genetic changes can occur at different levels and by different mechanisms.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The gain or loss of an entire chromosome can occur through errors in mitosis.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] More common are mutations, which are changes in the nucleotide sequence of genomic DNA.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Large-scale mutations involve the deletion or gain of a portion of a chromosome.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Genomic amplification occurs when a cell gains copies (often 20 or more) of a small chromosomal locus, usually containing one or more oncogenes and adjacent genetic material.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Translocation occurs when two separate chromosomal regions become abnormally fused, often at a characteristic location.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] A well-known example of this is the Philadelphia chromosome, or translocation of chromosomes 9 and 22, which occurs in chronic myelogenous leukemia and results in production of the BCR-Abl fusion protein, an oncogenic tyrosine kinase.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Small-scale mutations include point mutations, deletions, and insertions, which may occur in the promoter region of a gene and affect its expression, or may occur in the gene's coding sequence and alter the function or stability of its protein product.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Disruption of a single gene may also result from integration of genomic material from a DNA virus or retrovirus, leading to the expression of *viral* oncogenes in the affected cell and its descendants.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Replication of the data contained within the DNA of living cells will probabilistically result in some errors (mutations).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Complex error correction and prevention are built into the process and safeguard the cell against cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] If a significant error occurs, the damaged cell can self-destruct through programmed cell death, termed apoptosis.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] If the error control processes fail, then the mutations will survive and be passed along to daughter cells.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Some environments make errors more likely to arise and propagate.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Such environments can include the presence of disruptive substances called carcinogens, repeated physical injury, heat, ionising radiation, or hypoxia.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The transformation of a normal cell into cancer is akin to a chain reaction caused by initial errors, which compound into more severe errors, each progressively allowing the cell to escape more controls that limit normal tissue growth.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] This rebellion-like scenario is an undesirable survival of the fittest, where the driving forces of evolution work against the body's design and enforcement of order.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Once cancer has begun to develop, this ongoing process, termed *clonal evolution*, drives progression towards more invasive stages.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Clonal evolution leads to intra-tumour heterogeneity (cancer cells with heterogeneous mutations) that complicates the design of effective treatments, as therapies must account for the selective pressures they exert on the tumour cell population.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The classical view of cancer is a set of diseases driven by progressive genetic abnormalities that include mutations in tumor-suppressor genes and oncogenes, and in chromosomal abnormalities.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] A role for epigenetic alterations was identified in the early 21st century.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Epigenetic alterations are functionally relevant modifications to the genome that do not change the nucleotide sequence.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Examples of such modifications are changes in DNA methylation (hypermethylation and hypomethylation), histone modification and changes in chromosomal architecture (caused by inappropriate expression of proteins such as HMGA2 or HMGA1).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Each of these alterations regulates gene expression without altering the underlying DNA sequence.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] These changes may remain through cell divisions, endure for multiple generations, and can be considered as equivalent to mutations.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Epigenetic alterations occur frequently in cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] As an example, one study listed protein coding genes that were frequently altered in their methylation in association with colon cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] These included 147 hypermethylated and 27 hypomethylated genes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Of the hypermethylated genes, 10 were hypermethylated in 100% of colon cancers and many others were hypermethylated in more than 50% of colon cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] While epigenetic alterations are found in cancers, the epigenetic alterations in DNA repair genes, causing reduced expression of DNA repair proteins, may be of particular importance.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Such alterations may occur early in the progression to cancer and are a possible cause of the genetic instability characteristic of cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Reduced expression of DNA repair genes disrupts DNA repair.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] This is shown in the figure at the 4th level from the top.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] (In the figure, red wording indicates the central role of DNA damage and defects in DNA repair in the progression to cancer.) When DNA repair is deficient DNA damage remains in cells at a higher than usual level (5th level) and causes increased frequencies of mutation and/or epimutation (6th level).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Mutation rates increase substantially in cells defective in DNA mismatch repair or in homologous recombinational repair (HRR).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Chromosomal rearrangements and aneuploidy (an abnormal number of chromosomes in a cell) also increase in HRR defective cells.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Higher levels of DNA damage cause increased mutation (right side of figure) and increased epimutation.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] During repair of DNA double strand breaks, or repair of other DNA damage, incompletely cleared repair sites can cause epigenetic gene silencing.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Deficient expression of DNA repair proteins due to an inherited mutation can increase cancer risks.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Individuals with an inherited impairment in any of 34 DNA repair genes (see article DNA repair-deficiency disorder) have increased cancer risk, with some defects ensuring a 100% lifetime chance of cancer (e.g. p53 mutations).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Germline DNA repair mutations are noted on the figure's left side.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] However, such germline mutations (which cause highly penetrant cancer syndromes) are the cause of only about 1 percent of cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In sporadic cancers, deficiencies in DNA repair are occasionally caused by a mutation in a DNA repair gene but are much more frequently caused by epigenetic alterations that reduce or silence expression of DNA repair genes.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] This is indicated in the figure at the 3rd level.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Many studies of heavy metal-induced carcinogenesis show that such heavy metals cause a reduction in expression of DNA repair enzymes, some through epigenetic mechanisms.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] DNA repair inhibition is proposed to be a predominant mechanism in heavy metal-induced carcinogenicity.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In addition, frequent epigenetic alterations of the DNA sequences code for small RNAs called microRNAs (or miRNAs). miRNAs do not code for proteins, but can "target" protein-coding genes and reduce their expression.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancers usually arise from an assemblage of mutations and epimutations that confer a selective advantage leading to clonal expansion (see Field defects in progression to cancer).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Mutations, however, may not be as frequent in cancers as epigenetic alterations.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] An average cancer of the breast or colon can have about 60 to 70 protein-altering mutations, of which about three or four may be "driver" mutations and the remaining ones may be "passenger" mutations.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The typical steps in metastasis are local invasion, intravasation (entry of cancer cells into a blood or lymph vessel), circulation through the body, extravasation (exit from the vessel into surrounding tissue), proliferation and angiogenesis (formation of new blood vessels to supply the tumour).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Different types of cancers tend to metastasize to particular organs, but overall the most common places for metastases to occur are the lungs, liver, brain and the bones.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Normal cells typically generate about 30% of energy from glycolysis, whereas most cancers rely on glycolysis for energy production (Warburg effect).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] But a minority of cancer types rely on oxidative phosphorylation as the primary energy source, including lymphoma, leukemia, and endometrial cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Even in these cases, however, the use of glycolysis as an energy source rarely exceeds 60%.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] A few cancers use glutamine as the major energy source, partly because it provides nitrogen required for nucleotide (DNA, RNA) synthesis.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer stem cells often use oxidative phosphorylation or glutamine as a primary energy source.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Most cancers are initially recognized either because of the appearance of signs or symptoms or through screening.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Neither of these leads to a definitive diagnosis, which requires the examination of a tissue sample by a pathologist.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] People with suspected cancer are investigated with medical tests.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] These commonly include blood tests, X-rays, (contrast) CT scans and endoscopy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The tissue diagnosis from the biopsy indicates the type of cell that is proliferating, its histological grade, genetic abnormalities and other features.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Together, this information is useful to evaluate the prognosis and to choose the best treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cytogenetics and immunohistochemistry are other types of tissue tests.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] These tests provide information about molecular changes (such as mutations, fusion genes and numerical chromosome changes) and may thus also indicate the prognosis and best treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer diagnosis can cause psychological distress and psychosocial interventions, such as talking therapy, may help people with this.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Some people choose to disclose the diagnosis widely; others prefer to keep the information private, especially shortly after the diagnosis, or to disclose it only partially or to selected people.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancers are classified by the type of cell that the tumor cells resemble and is therefore presumed to be the origin of the tumor.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancers are usually named using *-carcinoma*, *-sarcoma* or *-blastoma* as a suffix, with the Latin or Greek word for the organ or tissue of origin as the root.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For example, cancers of the liver parenchyma arising from malignant epithelial cells is called *hepatocarcinoma*, while a malignancy arising from primitive liver precursor cells is called a hepatoblastoma and a cancer arising from fat cells is called a *liposarcoma*.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For some common cancers, the English organ name is used.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For example, the most common type of breast cancer is called *ductal carcinoma of the breast*.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Here, the adjective *ductal* refers to the appearance of cancer under the microscope, which suggests that it has originated in the milk ducts.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Benign tumors (which are not cancers) are named using *-oma* as a suffix with the organ name as the root.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For example, a benign tumor of smooth muscle cells is called a *leiomyoma* (the common name of this frequently occurring benign tumor in the uterus is *fibroid*).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Confusingly, some types of cancer use the *-noma* suffix, examples including melanoma and seminoma.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Some types of cancer are named for the size and shape of the cells under a microscope, such as giant cell carcinoma, spindle cell carcinoma and small-cell carcinoma.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention involves changes on the individual level, as well as the public policy level.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Around 40% of cancer can be prevented by avoiding or eliminating risk factors.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention is more cost-effective than treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] On an individual level, cancer can be prevented by avoiding carcinogens such as with smoking, limiting sun exposure, maintaining a healthy weight and active lifestyle, and following medical guidance designed to decrease risk for cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Public policy changes are required to expand individual access to cancer prevention interventions, as well as to address collective issues that cause cancer such as air pollution.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Due to having shared causes in common, efforts to prevent cancer often help prevent other diseases as well as improve the environment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention through diet generally emphasizes broad, healthy eating habits over focusing on specific foods.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The risk for cancer is decreased with a diet high in fiber, fruits and vegetables, and low in red and processed meat.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Replacing refined sugars with whole grains, and consuming plant-based proteins and fats also helps reduce the risk of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Maintaining a healthy body weight and being physically active helps prevent cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Obesity increases the risk for cancer, partly through causing inflammation and metabolic and hormonal abnormalities.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Exercise promotes healthy immune and hormonal systems that reduce cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Diets high in calcium (such as dairy products) and coffee, and low in processed meat, can help prevent colorectal cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Alcohol is a group 1 carcinogen, and is responsible for around 4% of all cancer deaths.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Any amount of alcohol increases the risk for cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Alcohol causes several types of cancer, through different mechanisms including the breakdown of ethanol into acetaldehyde, which damages DNA.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Alcohol increases estrogen, which contributes to the development of breast cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Alcohol acts as a solvent for some carcinogens, allowing them to penetrate cells more easily.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] For instance, consuming alcohol along with tobacco helps carcinogens in tobacco penetrate the cells of the mouth and cause mouth cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Smoking is the number one preventable cause of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Smoking causes at least 20 different types of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cigars, pipes (including water pipes), and smokeless tobacco cause cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] More than 1.2 million people die every year from exposure to second-hand smoke, around 100,000 of these deaths from cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The health impact of electronic cigarettes (vaping) and similar products is unknown and subject to debate.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Breastfeeding reduces the mother's risk for developing breast cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Infants who breastfed are less likely to gain excess weight later in life.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] A healthy weight helps to reduce the risk for several types of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Ultraviolet radiation is the main cause of skin cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The incidence of skin cancer is increasing, and it is the most common type of cancer in lighter-skinned populations.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] UV radiation, whether from sunlight or tanning beds, directly and indirectly damages DNA.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The most effective way to prevent skin cancer is to limit sun exposure and not use tanning beds, wear protective clothing (such as a hat), wear sunscreen, and make use of the shade.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The best time to avoid sunlight is between 9:00 a.m. and 3:00 p.m. when UV radiation is strongest.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Even on cloudy days about 80% of UV radiation is still present.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] UV radiation does not correlate with temperature—there is just as much UV radiation from the sun on a cold day as on a hot day.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] About 10% of UVB radiation passes through glass windows.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] UV exposure during childhood is particularly harmful.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] However, the beneficial effects of sunlight exposure (such as the production of vitamin D) can be achieved while avoiding harmful amounts of sun exposure.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The ozone layer absorbs UV radiation from the sun, reducing rates of skin cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] However, atmospheric pollution has decreased the ozone layer, and increased rates of skin cancer globally.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In 1987, an international treaty named the Montreal Protocol was signed to limit the release of ozone-damaging chemicals.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Since then the ozone layer has been recovering, and it is expected that by 2100 the Montreal Protocol will have prevented 11 million cases of melanoma in the United States.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Air pollution, both outdoor and indoor, is the largest environmental contributor to cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Air pollution caused an estimated 350,167 deaths from lung cancer in 2017.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Airborne particulate matter smaller than 2.5 µm (PM2.5) is a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The concentration of PM2.5 in the air is the most reliable predictor of how carcinogenic the air is.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] PM2.5 primarily comes from the burning of fuel for transportation, power generation, and industry, the burning of biomass (e.g. forest fires, stubble burning), and heating and cooking in the home.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In 2017, an estimated 14.1% of all lung cancer deaths were caused by PM2.5 pollution.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Local PM2.5 and PM10 levels can be monitored online, and wearing a close-fitting particulate respirator reduces personal exposure when levels are high.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Exposure to cancer-causing air pollution can also be reduced by avoiding motorized transportation, selecting routes away from pollution sources such as coal plants, and keeping vehicle windows closed in heavy traffic.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Decreasing outdoor air pollution requires action on the public policy level, and involves international collaborative efforts.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Indoor air pollution includes PM2.5 from the burning of fuels, as well as other pollutants such as radon and hazardous construction materials (e.g. asbestos, glues, formaldehyde, lead).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In 2019, the percent of preventable cases of lung cancer by cause was estimated as 62% for smoking, 15% for PM2.5 in outdoor air, 5.8% for secondhand smoke, 4% from using solid fuels for cooking, and 4% for radon.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Individuals can decrease air pollution in the home by using clean fuels, maintaining adequate ventilation, and using air purifiers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Around 80% of ionizing radiation that people are exposed to comes from natural sources, around half of which comes from breathing in radioactive radon gas.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Radon is produced by the decay of uranium in the ground, becoming a radioactive gas that can accumulate in the buildings above it.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Exposure to radon can be reduced by testing homes and, when found to be high, taking steps to reduce indoor radon levels.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] The primary method to reduce indoor radon levels is a vent pipe system and fan, which pulls radon from beneath the building and vents it to the outside.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Around 20% of ionizing radiation that people are exposed to comes from artificial sources, primarily from x-rays used for medical imaging.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] CT scans, which take x-rays at many angles to produce a 3D image, expose patients to a higher level of radiation than standard 2D x-rays.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention focuses on avoiding unnecessary diagnostic procedures, and minimizing the dose of ionizing radiation that patients are exposed to during these procedures.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] There have been 38 workplace chemicals and 12 workplace circumstances classified as carcinogenic, and 41 chemicals and 6 circumstances classified as probably carcinogenic.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Despite being known to cause cancer, workers are still commonly exposed to silica, diesel engine exhaust, heavy metals, asbestos, and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Occupational cancer can be reduced, and in recent decades successful regulations and programs have reduced or eliminated exposure to certain carcinogens in the workplace.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Prevention involves decreasing the use of certain chemicals and if this isn't possible limiting exposure to these substances, a process known as hierarchy of controls.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Occupational cancer can also be prevented by improving workplace procedures and training, and by using personal protective equipment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In 2018, 2.2 million cases of cancer were caused by infection, primarily by *Helicobacter pylori* (810,000), human papillomavirus (690,000), hepatitis B (360,000), and hepatitis C (160,000).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] All four of these infections can either be vaccinated against or treated, and collectively they cause more than 90% of infection-related cancers worldwide.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Medications can be used to prevent cancer in a few circumstances.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] In the general population, NSAIDs reduce the risk of colorectal cancer; however, due to cardiovascular and gastrointestinal side effects, they cause more harm than benefit when used for prevention.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Aspirin is not recommended for reducing cancer risk.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] COX-2 inhibitors may decrease the rate of polyp formation in people with familial adenomatous polyposis; however, it is associated with the same adverse effects as NSAIDs.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Women who have an increased risk for breast cancer can lower their chances of getting breast cancer by taking tamoxifen, raloxifene, or aromatase inhibitors.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] No vitamin, multivitamin, or nutritional supplement is recommended for the prevention of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Vitamin E supplements do not prevent cancer, and beta-carotene supplements increase the odds of lung cancer in those already at a high risk for it.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Hormone-sensitive cancers are dependent on hormones for growth and survival.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Medications that effect hormone levels may therefore have a harmful or beneficial effect on cancer rates.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Women who are on, or recently took, combined oral contraceptives (COCs) have an increased risk for breast cancer and cervical cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] However, CBCs also decrease the risk for ovarian cancer, and this protective effect continues years after stopping their use.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Estrogen-only menopausal hormone therapy increases the risk of breast, endometrial, and ovarian cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p01] Combined estrogen–progestogen hormone therapy increases the risk of breast and endometrial cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Unlike diagnostic efforts prompted by symptoms and medical signs, cancer screening involves efforts to detect cancer after it has formed, but before any noticeable symptoms appear.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] This may involve physical examination, blood or urine tests or medical imaging.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Cancer screening is not available for many types of cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Even when tests are available, they may not be recommended for everyone.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] *Universal screening* or *mass screening* involves screening everyone.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] *Selective screening* identifies people who are at higher risk, such as people with a family history.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Several factors are considered to determine whether the benefits of screening outweigh the risks and the costs of screening.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Screens for gastric cancer using photofluorography due to the high incidence there.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Genetic testing for individuals at high risk of certain cancers is recommended by unofficial groups.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Carriers of these mutations may then undergo enhanced surveillance, chemoprevention, or preventative surgery to reduce their subsequent risk.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Many treatment options for cancer exist.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The primary ones include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, hormonal therapy, targeted therapy and palliative care.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Which treatments are used depends on the type, location and grade of the cancer as well as the patient's health and preferences.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The treatment intent may or may not be curative.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Chemotherapy is the treatment of cancer with one or more cytotoxic anti-neoplastic drugs (chemotherapeutic agents) as part of a standardized regimen.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The term encompasses a variety of drugs, which are divided into broad categories such as alkylating agents and antimetabolites.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Traditional chemotherapeutic agents act by killing cells that divide rapidly, a critical property of most cancer cells.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] It was found that providing combined cytotoxic drugs is better than a single drug, a process called the combination therapy, which has an advantage in the statistics of survival and response to the tumor and in the progress of the disease.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] A Cochrane review concluded that combined therapy was more effective in treating metastasized breast cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] However, generally it is not certain whether combination chemotherapy leads to better health outcomes, when both survival and toxicity are considered.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Targeted therapy is a form of chemotherapy that targets specific molecular differences between cancer and normal cells.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The first targeted therapies blocked the estrogen receptor molecule, inhibiting the growth of breast cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Another common example is the class of Bcr-Abl inhibitors, which are used to treat chronic myelogenous leukemia (CML).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Currently, targeted therapies exist for many of the most common cancer types, including bladder cancer, breast cancer, colorectal cancer, kidney cancer, leukemia, liver cancer, lung cancer, lymphoma, pancreatic cancer, prostate cancer, skin cancer, and thyroid cancer as well as other cancer types.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The efficacy of chemotherapy depends on the type of cancer and the stage.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In combination with surgery, chemotherapy has proven useful in cancer types including breast cancer, colorectal cancer, pancreatic cancer, osteogenic sarcoma, testicular cancer, ovarian cancer and certain lung cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Chemotherapy is curative for some cancers, such as some leukemias, ineffective in some brain tumors, and needless in others, such as most non-melanoma skin cancers.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The effectiveness of chemotherapy is often limited by its toxicity to other tissues in the body.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Even when chemotherapy does not provide a permanent cure, it may be useful to reduce symptoms such as pain or to reduce the size of an inoperable tumor in the hope that surgery will become possible in the future.*Wang M, Zhang C, Yang G, Shi Y (March 2017).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] "Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy Creates Surgery Opportunities For Inoperable Locally Advanced Breast Cancer".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Radiation therapy involves the use of ionizing radiation in an attempt to either cure or improve symptoms.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] It works by damaging the DNA of cancerous tissue, causing mitotic catastrophe resulting in the death of the cancer cells.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] To spare normal tissues (such as skin or organs, which radiation must pass through to treat the tumor), shaped radiation beams are aimed from multiple exposure angles to intersect at the tumor, providing a much larger dose there than in the surrounding, healthy tissue.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] As with chemotherapy, cancers vary in their response to radiation therapy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Radiation therapy is used in about half of cases.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The radiation can be either from internal sources (brachytherapy) or external sources.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The radiation is most commonly low energy X-rays for treating skin cancers, while higher energy X-rays are used for cancers within the body.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Radiation is typically used in addition to surgery and/or chemotherapy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] For certain types of cancer, such as early head and neck cancer, it may be used alone.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Radiation therapy after surgery for brain metastases has been shown to not improve overall survival in patients compared to surgery alone.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] For painful bone metastasis, radiation therapy has been found to be effective in about 70% of patients.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Surgery is the primary method of treatment for most isolated, solid cancers and may play a role in palliation and prolongation of survival.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] It is typically an important part of the definitive diagnosis and staging of tumors, as biopsies are usually required.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In localized cancer, surgery typically attempts to remove the entire mass along with, in certain cases, the lymph nodes in the area.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] For some types of cancer this is sufficient to eliminate the cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Palliative care may be confused with hospice and therefore only indicated when people approach end of life.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Like hospice care, palliative care attempts to help the patient cope with their immediate needs and to increase comfort.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Unlike hospice care, palliative care does not require people to stop treatment aimed at the cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Multiple national medical guidelines recommend early palliative care for patients whose cancer has produced distressing symptoms or who need help coping with their illness.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In patients first diagnosed with metastatic disease, palliative care may be immediately indicated.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Palliative care is indicated for patients with a prognosis of less than 12 months of life even given aggressive treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] A variety of therapies using immunotherapy, stimulating or helping the immune system to fight cancer, have come into use since 1997.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Laser therapy uses high-intensity light to treat cancer by shrinking or destroying tumors or precancerous growths.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Lasers are most commonly used to treat superficial cancers that are on the surface of the body or the lining of internal organs.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] It is used to treat basal cell skin cancer and the very early stages of others like cervical, penile, vaginal, vulvar, and non-small cell lung cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] It is often combined with other treatments, such as surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Laser-induced interstitial thermotherapy (LITT), or interstitial laser photocoagulation, uses lasers to treat some cancers using hyperthermia, which uses heat to shrink tumors by damaging or killing cancer cells.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Lasers are more precise than surgery and cause less damage, pain, bleeding, swelling, and scarring.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] A disadvantage is that surgeons must have specialized training.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] It may be more expensive than other treatments.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Complementary and alternative cancer treatments are a diverse group of therapies, practices and products that are not part of conventional medicine.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] "Complementary medicine" refers to methods and substances used along with conventional medicine, while "alternative medicine" refers to compounds used instead of conventional medicine.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Most complementary and alternative medicines for cancer have not been studied or tested using conventional techniques such as clinical trials.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Some alternative treatments have been investigated and shown to be ineffective but still continue to be marketed and promoted.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Survival rates vary by cancer type and by the stage at which it is diagnosed, ranging from majority survival to complete mortality five years after diagnosis.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Once a cancer has metastasized, prognosis normally becomes much worse.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] About half of patients receiving treatment for invasive cancer (excluding carcinoma *in situ* and non-melanoma skin cancers) die from that cancer or its treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] A majority of cancer deaths are due to metastases of the primary tumor.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Survival is worse in the developing world, partly because the types of cancer that are most common there are harder to treat than those associated with developed countries.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Those who survive cancer develop a second primary cancer at about twice the rate of those never diagnosed.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Predicting short- or long-term survival depends on many factors.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The most important are the cancer type and the patient's age and overall health.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Those who are frail with other health problems have lower survival rates than otherwise healthy people.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Centenarians are unlikely to survive for five years even if treatment is successful.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] People who report a higher quality of life tend to survive longer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] People with lower quality of life may be affected by depression and other complications and/or disease progression that both impairs quality and quantity of life.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Additionally, patients with worse prognoses may be depressed or report poorer quality of life because they perceive that their condition is likely to be fatal.*Satin JR, Linden W, Phillips MJ (November 2009).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] "Depression as a predictor of disease progression and mortality in cancer patients: a meta-analysis".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] People with cancer have an increased risk of blood clots in their veins which can be life-threatening.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The use of blood thinners such as heparin decrease the risk of blood clots but have not been shown to increase survival in people with cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] People who take blood thinners also have an increased risk of bleeding.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Although extremely rare, some forms of cancer, even from an advanced stage, can heal spontaneously.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] This phenomenon is known as spontaneous remission.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Estimates are that in 2018, 18.1 million new cases of cancer and 9.6 million deaths occur globally.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] About 20% of males and 17% of females will get cancer at some point in time while 13% of males and 9% of females will die from it.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In 2008, approximately 12.7 million cancers were diagnosed (excluding non-melanoma skin cancers and other non-invasive cancers) and in 2010 nearly 7.98 million people died.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Cancers account for almost one in six deaths.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The cancers causing the most deaths, as of 2020 are lung cancer (1.8 million), colorectal cancer (916,000), liver cancer (830,000), stomach cancer (769,000) and breast cancer (685,000).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] This makes invasive cancer the leading cause of death in the developed world and the second leading in the developing world.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Over half of these cases occur in the developing world.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Deaths from cancer were 5.8 million in 1990.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Deaths have been increasing primarily due to longer lifespans and lifestyle changes in the developing world.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The most significant risk factor for developing cancer is age.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Although it is possible for cancer to strike at any age, most patients with invasive cancer are over 65.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] According to cancer researcher Robert A.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Weinberg, "If we lived long enough, sooner or later we all would get cancer." Some of the association between aging and cancer is attributed to immunosenescence, errors accumulated in DNA over a lifetime and age-related changes in the endocrine system.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Aging's effect on cancer is complicated by factors such as DNA damage and inflammation promoting it and factors such as vascular aging and endocrine changes inhibiting it.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Some slow-growing cancers are particularly common, but often are not fatal.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Autopsy studies in Europe and Asia showed that up to 36% of people have undiagnosed and apparently harmless thyroid cancer at the time of their deaths and that 80% of men develop prostate cancer by age 80.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] As these cancers do not cause the patient's death, identifying them would have represented overdiagnosis rather than useful medical care.*Lowenstein LM, Basourakos SP, Williams MD, Troncoso P, Gregg JR, Thompson TC, et al.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] "Active surveillance for prostate and thyroid cancers: evolution in clinical paradigms and lessons learned".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The three most common childhood cancers are leukemia (34%), brain tumors (23%) and lymphomas (12%).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In the United States, cancer affects about 1 in 285 children.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Rates of childhood cancer increased by 0.6% per year between 1975 and 2002 in the United States and by 1.1% per year between 1978 and 1997 in Europe.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Death from childhood cancer decreased by half between 1975 and 2010 in the United States.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Cancer has existed for all of human history.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The earliest written record regarding cancer is from c.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] 1600 BC in the Egyptian Edwin Smith Papyrus and describes breast cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] 370 BC) described several kinds of cancer, referring to them with the Greek word καρκίνος *karkinos* (crab or crayfish).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] This name comes from the appearance of the cut surface of a solid malignant tumor, with "the veins stretched on all sides as the animal the crab has its feet, whence it derives its name".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Galen stated that "cancer of the breast is so called because of the fancied resemblance to a crab given by the lateral prolongations of the tumor and the adjacent distended veins".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] 25 BC – 50 AD) translated *karkinos* into Latin as *cancer*, also meaning crab and recommended surgery as treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Galen (2nd century AD) disagreed with the use of surgery and recommended purgatives instead.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] These recommendations largely stood for 1000 years.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In the 15th, 16th and 17th centuries, it became acceptable for doctors to dissect bodies to discover the cause of death.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The German professor Wilhelm Fabry believed that breast cancer was caused by a milk clot in a mammary duct.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The Dutch professor Francois de la Boe Sylvius, a follower of Descartes, believed that all disease was the outcome of chemical processes and that acidic lymph fluid was the cause of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] His contemporary Nicolaes Tulp believed that cancer was a poison that slowly spreads and concluded that it was contagious.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The physician John Hill described tobacco sniffing as the cause of nose cancer in 1761.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] This was followed by the report in 1775 by British surgeon Percivall Pott that chimney sweeps' carcinoma, a cancer of the scrotum, was a common disease among chimney sweeps.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] With the widespread use of the microscope in the 18th century, it was discovered that the 'cancer poison' spread from the primary tumor through the lymph nodes to other sites ("metastasis").
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] This view of the disease was first formulated by the English surgeon Campbell De Morgan between 1871 and 1874.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Although many diseases (such as heart failure) may have a worse prognosis than most cases of cancer, cancer is the subject of widespread fear and taboos.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The euphemism of "a long illness" to describe cancers leading to death is still commonly used in obituaries, rather than naming the disease explicitly, reflecting an apparent stigma.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Cancer is also euphemised as "the C-word"; Macmillan Cancer Support uses the term to try to lessen the fear around the disease.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In Nigeria, one local name for cancer translates into English as "the disease that cannot be cured".
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Western conceptions of patients' rights for people with cancer include a duty to fully disclose the medical situation to the person, and the right to engage in shared decision-making in a way that respects the person's own values.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In other cultures, other rights and values are preferred.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] For example, most African cultures value whole families rather than individualism.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In parts of Africa, a diagnosis is commonly made so late that cure is not possible, and treatment, if available at all, would quickly bankrupt the family.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] As a result of these factors, African healthcare providers tend to let family members decide whether, when and how to disclose the diagnosis, and they tend to do so slowly and circuitously, as the person shows interest and an ability to cope with the grim news.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] People from Asian and South American countries also tend to prefer a slower, less candid approach to disclosure than is idealized in the United States and Western Europe, and they believe that sometimes it would be preferable not to be told about a cancer diagnosis.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In general, disclosure of the diagnosis is more common than it was in the 20th century, but full disclosure of the prognosis is not offered to many patients around the world.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In the United States and some other cultures, cancer is regarded as a disease that must be "fought" to end the "civil insurrection"; a war on cancer was declared in the US.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Military metaphors are particularly common in descriptions of cancer's human effects, and they emphasize both the state of the patient's health and the need to take immediate, decisive actions himself rather than to delay, to ignore or to rely entirely on others.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The military metaphors also help rationalize radical, destructive treatments.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In the 1970s, a relatively popular alternative cancer treatment in the US was a specialized form of talk therapy, based on the idea that cancer was caused by a bad attitude.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] People with a "cancer personality"—depressed, repressed, self-loathing and afraid to express their emotions—were believed to have manifested cancer through subconscious desire.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Some psychotherapists claimed that treatment to change the patient's outlook on life would cure the cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Among other effects, this belief allowed society to blame the victim for having caused the cancer (by "wanting" it) or having prevented its cure (by not becoming a sufficiently happy, fearless and loving person).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] It also increased patients' anxiety, as they incorrectly believed that natural emotions of sadness, anger or fear shorten their lives.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The idea was ridiculed by Susan Sontag, who published *Illness as Metaphor* while recovering from treatment for breast cancer in 1978.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Although the original idea is now generally regarded as nonsense, the idea partly persists in a reduced form with a widespread, but incorrect, belief that deliberately cultivating a habit of positive thinking will increase survival.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] This notion is particularly strong in breast cancer culture.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] One idea about why people with cancer are blamed or stigmatized, called the just-world fallacy, is that blaming cancer on the patient's actions or attitudes allows the blamers to regain a sense of control.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] This is based upon the blamers' belief that the world is fundamentally just and so any dangerous illness, like cancer, must be a type of punishment for bad choices, because in a just world, bad things would not happen to good people.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The total health care expenditure on cancer in the US was estimated to be $80.2 billion in 2015.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Even though cancer-related health care expenditure have increased in absolute terms during recent decades, the share of health expenditure devoted to cancer treatment has remained close to 5% between the 1960s and 2004.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] A similar pattern has been observed in Europe where about 6% of all health care expenditure are spent on cancer treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In addition to health care expenditure and financial toxicity, cancer causes indirect costs in the form of productivity losses due to sick days, permanent incapacity and disability as well as premature death during working age.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Cancer causes also costs for informal care.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Indirect costs and informal care costs are typically estimated to exceed or equal the health care costs of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] A study found women were around six times more likely to be divorced soon after a diagnosis of cancer compared to men.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Rate of separation for cancer-survivors showed correlations with race, age, income, and comorbidities in a study.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] A review found a somewhat decreased divorce rate for most cancer types, and noted study heterogeneity and methodological weaknesses for many studies on the effects of cancer on divorce.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Because cancer is a class of diseases, it is unlikely that there will ever be a single "cure for cancer" any more than there will be a single treatment for all infectious diseases.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Angiogenesis inhibitors were once incorrectly thought to have potential as a "silver bullet" treatment applicable to many types of cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Angiogenesis inhibitors and other cancer therapeutics are used in combination to reduce cancer morbidity and mortality.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Experimental cancer treatments are studied in clinical trials to compare the proposed treatment to the best existing treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Treatments that succeeded in one cancer type can be tested against other types.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Diagnostic tests are under development to better target the right therapies to the right patients, based on their individual biology.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The improved understanding of molecular biology and cellular biology due to cancer research has led to new treatments for cancer since US President Richard Nixon declared the "war on cancer" in 1971.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Since then, the country has spent over $200 billion on cancer research, including resources from public and private sectors.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The cancer death rate (adjusting for size and age of the population) declined by five percent between 1950 and 2005.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Competition for financial resources appears to have suppressed the creativity, cooperation, risk-taking and original thinking required to make fundamental discoveries, unduly favoring low-risk research into small incremental advancements over riskier, more innovative research.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Other consequences of competition appear to be many studies with dramatic claims whose results cannot be replicated and perverse incentives that encourage grantee institutions to grow without making sufficient investments in their own faculty and facilities.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Virotherapy, which uses oncolytic viruses, is being studied.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In the wake of the COVID-19 pandemic, there has been a worry that cancer research and treatment are slowing down.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Cancer affects approximately 1 in 1,000 pregnant women.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The most common cancers found during pregnancy are the same as the most common cancers found in non-pregnant women during childbearing ages: breast cancer, cervical cancer, leukemia, lymphoma, melanoma, ovarian cancer and colorectal cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Diagnosing a new cancer in a pregnant woman is difficult, in part because any symptoms are commonly assumed to be a normal discomfort associated with pregnancy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] As a result, cancer is typically discovered at a somewhat later stage than average.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Some imaging procedures, such as MRIs (magnetic resonance imaging), CT scans, ultrasounds and mammograms with fetal shielding are considered safe during pregnancy; some others, such as PET scans, are not.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Treatment is generally the same as for non-pregnant women.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] However, radiation and radioactive drugs are normally avoided during pregnancy, especially if the fetal dose might exceed 100 cGy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In some cases, some or all treatments are postponed until after birth if the cancer is diagnosed late in the pregnancy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Early deliveries are often used to advance the start of treatment.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Surgery is generally safe, but pelvic surgeries during the first trimester may cause miscarriage.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Some treatments, especially certain chemotherapy drugs given during the first trimester, increase the risk of birth defects and pregnancy loss (spontaneous abortions and stillbirths).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Elective abortions are not required and, for the most common forms and stages of cancer, do not improve the mother's survival.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In a few instances, such as advanced uterine cancer, the pregnancy cannot be continued and in others, the patient may end the pregnancy so that she can begin aggressive chemotherapy.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Some treatments can interfere with the mother's ability to give birth vaginally or to breastfeed.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Cervical cancer may require birth by Caesarean section.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Radiation to the breast reduces the ability of that breast to produce milk and increases the risk of mastitis.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Also, when chemotherapy is given after birth, many of the drugs appear in breast milk, which could harm the baby.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Veterinary oncology, concentrating mainly on cats and dogs, is a growing specialty in wealthy countries and the major forms of human treatment such as surgery and radiotherapy may be offered.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] The most common types of cancer differ, but the cancer burden seems at least as high in pets as in humans.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Animals, typically rodents, are often used in cancer research and studies of natural cancers in larger animals may benefit research into human cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Across wild animals, there is still limited data on cancer.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] Nonetheless, a study published in 2022, explored cancer risk in (non-domesticated) zoo mammals, belonging to 191 species for a total of 110,148 individuals, demonstrated that cancer is a ubiquitous disease of mammals and it can emerge anywhere along the mammalian phylogeny.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] This research also highlighted that cancer risk is not uniformly distributed along mammals.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] For instance, species in the order Carnivora are particularly prone to be affected by cancer (e.g. over 25% of clouded leopards, bat-eared foxes and red wolves die of cancer), while ungulates (especially even-toed ungulates) appear to face consistently low cancer risks.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] In non-humans, a few types of transmissible cancer have also been described, wherein the cancer spreads between animals by transmission of the tumor cells themselves.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/cancer-p02] This phenomenon is seen in dogs with Sticker's sarcoma (also known as canine transmissible venereal tumor), and in Tasmanian devils with devil facial tumour disease (DFTD).
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Chalmers Hospital was founded by Alexander Chalmers (died 11 August 1835), a merchant of Banff, who left the whole of his estate to be applied, upon the death of his wife, towards funding and building a hospital for the people in the Royal Burgh of Banff.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Mrs Chalmers died in 1861, and Chalmers Hospital opened on 19 July 1864.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The original 'deed of mortification' set out that this was for any destitute sick persons born, domiciled or resident in the Banff area, although in 1929 the trustees successfully petitioned for the removal of this restriction.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Some major redevelopment work began in October 2008, after the hospital attracted criticism for not being up to date, with some of the interior features having been there since the Second World War.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital remained open during the work, although the Findlater ward services were moved to Campbell Hospital in Portsoy until the Findlater ward was refurbished, and Seafield and Deveron ward were merged.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The midwifery unit was demolished and rebuilt to provide modern facilities.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Numerous other internal changes were also made inside, including X-ray facilities being moved to a different area of the building.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The redevelopment also provided upgraded facilities for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy and podiatry.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The completion of the redevelopment was recognised with a visit by the Princess Royal in March 2012.
[src:aberdeen-maternity-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital is supported by GPs from Banff, Gamrie, Deveron, Macduff, Portsoy and Aberchirder Medical Practices.
